In a New Setting: St. Patrick's Cathedral-- A new view of New York's greatest completed sacred edifice, St. Patrick's (R.C.) Cathedral on the east side of Fifth Ave. between 50th and 51st Sts. Note the new store building in right foreground, just being completed and soon to be occupied by Saks & Co. This formerly was the site of the Democratic Club.
Jan. 12, 1924
Underwood & Underwood.

Said to be the most imposing Church edifice in the U.S. The spires rise to a height of 339 feet, and the building extends back 332 feet on the side streets. The Cathedral was begun in 1858 and dedicated 21 years later.

Celebrations, Parades and Municipal Events: Three additional views of the Chas. Francis Murphy funeral procession on 5th Avenue, approaching St. Patrick's Cathedral. The photographers vantage point is at the S.W. corner of 50th Street and he is viewing eastward and southeastward. See the N. Y. Times of April 26 to 29, 1924 for full account.

April 29, 1924
